00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:36.380
any QT liability for this compound.

802
00:47:37.100 --> 00:47:40.120
Of course, we have to test it in the clinic to be timely for real.

803
00:47:41.760 --> 00:47:44.560
Okay, please join me in thanking Martin for a fantastic talk.

804
00:47:50.430 --> 00:47:53.880
Okay, our next speaker is Smruthi Vijayaraghavan

805
00:47:54.360 --> 00:47:57.740
from J&amp;J. She's director and head of Solid Tumor Oncology

806
00:47:57.880 --> 00:47:58.460
Discovery.

807
00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:02.800
And today she'll be talking about the ENPP targeted ADC leveraging the

808
00:48:02.820 --> 00:48:03.700
auristatin platform.

809
00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:08.750
Thank you. And thank you to the organizers for this

810
00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:12.560
opportunity to present our pre-clinical work on our

811
00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:16.200
novel ENPP3 targeted ADC in solid tumors.

812
00:48:17.650 --> 00:48:19.200
So these are my disclosures.

813
00:48:20.740 --> 00:48:24.240
So I wanted to start with a little bit background on the target.

814
00:48:24.620 --> 00:48:27.460
So ENPP3 or ectonucleotide

815
00:48:27.820 --> 00:48:31.760
pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase is a type II transmembrane

816
00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:35.340
protein, and it's part of the cell surface ENPP family.

817
00:48:36.180 --> 00:48:39.930
In terms of its expression, ENPP3 has an apically

818
00:48:40.020 --> 00:48:43.400
restricted expression in most normal tissues,

819
00:48:43.980 --> 00:48:47.320
and this provides a unique opportunity being less

820
00:48:47.340 --> 00:48:49.480
accessible to systemic circulation.

821
00:48:50.100 --> 00:48:54.020
However, in tumors it is depolarized, making it more

822
00:48:54.060 --> 00:48:57.900
readily accessible to antibody-based therapeutics, and thus

823
00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:01.200
creates a more tumor-selective targeted opportunity.

824
00:49:02.700 --> 00:49:06.480
In addition to this difference in polarity, we also see elevated

825
00:49:06.540 --> 00:49:10.380
expression in several solid tumors of high unmet need.

826
00:49:11.820 --> 00:49:15.780
In terms of its function in normal tissues, ENPP3

827
00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:18.340
is known to hydrolyze extracellular

828
00:49:18.460 --> 00:49:22.150
pyrophosphatase/phosphodiesterase bonds and is also

829
00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:24.729
predicted to be a basophil activation marker.

830
00:49:25.419 --> 00:49:29.100
However, in tumors its role is really not well understood.

831
00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:34.240
So one of the first things to better understand the expression of ENPP3,

832
00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:38.580
we developed an immunohistochemistry or an IHC assay, and

833
00:49:38.660 --> 00:49:41.480
here looked at a panel of solid tumors.

834
00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:45.840
And as you can see on the graph on the left, we see broad and

835
00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:49.660
high ENPP3 expression across several solid tumors,

836
00:49:50.160 --> 00:49:53.960
including about 93% of clear cell renal cell carcinoma,

837
00:49:54.780 --> 00:49:58.440
78% of papillary renal cell carcinoma, and around

838
00:49:58.460 --> 00:50:01.489
45% to 50% in several solid tumors,

839
00:50:01.580 --> 00:50:04.820
including colorectal, lung adenocarcinoma, as well as

840
00:50:04.940 --> 00:50:06.300
endometrioid cancers.

841
00:50:07.200 --> 00:50:11.160
In addition to the high prevalence, the graphs on the right here

842
00:50:11.260 --> 00:50:15.240
also show that in the top three tumor types that are showing

843
00:50:15.300 --> 00:50:19.260
here, in addition to the high prevalence, we also see high percent

844
00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:23.040
positivity within these tumors. So I think this

845
00:50:23.140 --> 00:50:26.680
data really makes this a novel and attractive

846
00:50:26.800 --> 00:50:30.780
target for us to go after in several of these solid tumors

847
00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:34.280
of interest. And what I'm going to be talking about today is

848
00:50:34.380 --> 00:50:37.520
obviously our novel ENPP3 targeted

849
00:50:37.580 --> 00:50:41.540
ADC, and how we leverage this biology and expression to

850
00:50:41.560 --> 00:50:42.540
develop this asset.

851
00:50:44.040 --> 00:50:47.600
So before I get into the molecular design, just a little bit background on

852
00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:51.220
ADCs. I'm sure almost everyone here is aware that

853
00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:55.220
antibody-drug conjugates work based on binding of

854
00:50:55.260 --> 00:50:57.860
an antibody to a tumor-specific antigen.

855
00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:02.460
This results in internalization of the antibody, intracellular

856
00:51:02.580 --> 00:51:05.820
payload release, which in turn causes tumor cell killing.

857
00:51:07.020 --> 00:51:10.970
Over the last few years, ADCs have become a clinically validated

858
00:51:11.020 --> 00:51:14.640
modality in solid tumors. While that's quite exciting,

859
00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:18.840
one of the high unmet needs and the challenge still remains being

860
00:51:18.920 --> 00:51:22.800
able to find novel and clean targets within the solid

861
00:51:22.860 --> 00:51:26.840
tumor space. And I think that's where we have an advantage here

862
00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:30.780
with ENPP3, both leveraging the high levels of expression

863
00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:33.700
or prevalence as well as the apical restriction.

864
00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:38.840
So in terms of the actual molecular design, obviously one of the first

865
00:51:38.900 --> 00:51:41.440
key components here is our antibody.

866
00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:46.220
So through extensive screening, we identified our lead

867
00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:50.000
antibody binder, which is a high-affinity ENPP3

868
00:51:50.140 --> 00:51:54.040
specific binder, and it's bivalent to ENPP3 with

869
00:51:54.100 --> 00:51:55.120
no off-target

870
00:51:55.920 --> 00:51:56.300
binding.

871
00:51:57.120 --> 00:52:00.620
It shows rapid internalization as well as favorable

872
00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:03.980
biophysics, looking at stability, aggregation, and also

873
00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:05.040
manufacturability.

874
00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:09.980
So the second key component for the ADCs are

875
00:52:10.080 --> 00:52:12.720
obviously the linker payload platform.

876
00:52:12.840 --> 00:52:16.360
And for this, we leveraged the dolastatin

877
00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:20.140
platform, which we actually licensed from Mersana Therapeutics,

878
00:52:20.260 --> 00:52:21.840
now part of Day One Pharma.

879
00:52:22.840 --> 00:52:26.660
And one of the key components of this platform is actually the

880
00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:30.420
unique and novel auristatin-derived payload

881
00:52:30.460 --> 00:52:32.140
called the AFHPA.

882
00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:35.760
As you can see in the cartoon there at the bottom,

883
00:52:36.160 --> 00:52:39.640
AFHPA by itself is cell permeable and can cause

884
00:52:39.660 --> 00:52:43.260
bystander effect. However, within the tumor cells, it

885
00:52:43.340 --> 00:52:46.780
undergoes a metabolism where it cleaves off the

886
00:52:46.800 --> 00:52:50.560
HPA component, resulting in an auristatin F or an

887
00:52:50.620 --> 00:52:54.440
AF payload, and this does not have any bystander

888
00:52:54.480 --> 00:52:57.920
effect. So this actually results in a controlled

889
00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:00.120
bystander effect with our molecule.

890
00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:04.020
In terms of the conjugation, we have a site-specific

891
00:53:04.100 --> 00:53:08.099
conjugation with a branch linker that allows us to get

892
00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:11.880
a consistent molecular profile with a high stable and a

893
00:53:11.940 --> 00:53:12.660
uniform DAR.

894
00:53:13.590 --> 00:53:16.880
And in terms of biophysics, our ADC shows a favorable

895
00:53:16.980 --> 00:53:20.490
biophysical profile as well as stability and

896
00:53:20.520 --> 00:53:24.452
supports further development.So this, kind of the

897
00:53:24.492 --> 00:53:27.872
two key components that I described here, gets us to our

898
00:53:28.272 --> 00:53:31.712
actual lead molecule, which is our novel ENPP3-targeted

899
00:53:31.792 --> 00:53:35.612
ADC, JNJ-89862175, or

900
00:53:35.992 --> 00:53:38.592
JNJ-2175, as I'll call it hereafter.

901
00:53:40.312 --> 00:53:43.692
So in the next part, we're obviously sharing some of the preclinical

902
00:53:43.752 --> 00:53:46.032
characterization that we did with this molecule.

903
00:53:46.572 --> 00:53:49.752
So the first thing we looked at is we looked at binding.

904
00:53:49.872 --> 00:53:53.272
And as you can see there, we see potent

905
00:53:53.372 --> 00:53:56.672
dose-dependent binding of JNJ-2175 on

906
00:53:56.732 --> 00:54:00.172
ENPP3 positive cells, but no binding on

907
00:54:00.212 --> 00:54:04.092
ENPP3 negative cells. In addition, we also see

908
00:54:04.152 --> 00:54:07.512
no binding on ENPP1 and

909
00:54:07.572 --> 00:54:11.472
ENPP2 positive cell lines. So this confirms

910
00:54:11.512 --> 00:54:14.412
the specificity of JNJ-2175.

911
00:54:15.392 --> 00:54:19.292
The next thing we looked at is internalization, which, as

912
00:54:19.412 --> 00:54:23.112
I said, is one of the key components of an ADC.

913
00:54:24.082 --> 00:54:27.652
And here we performed a confocal live

914
00:54:27.752 --> 00:54:31.382
imaging on a panel of ENPP3 positive and

915
00:54:31.452 --> 00:54:35.272
negative cell lines. And the images that I'm showing here are on two

916
00:54:35.392 --> 00:54:38.892
positive cell lines with varying expression levels of

917
00:54:38.932 --> 00:54:41.512
ENPP3. And as you can see there,

918
00:54:41.772 --> 00:54:45.672
JNJ-2175, shown in the yellow dots, show

919
00:54:45.712 --> 00:54:48.752
potent internalization on both the cell lines.

920
00:54:49.612 --> 00:54:53.172
The quantification there at the bottom is the time course, and it

921
00:54:53.232 --> 00:54:56.882
shows that we do see rapid internalization with our

922
00:54:56.952 --> 00:54:57.352
molecule.

923
00:54:58.752 --> 00:55:02.712
So with these components, the next thing we wanted to look at was the in

924
00:55:02.752 --> 00:55:06.602
vitro potency of our molecule. And here we are looking

925
00:55:06.632 --> 00:55:10.572
at cytotoxicity on a panel of ENPP3 positive cell

926
00:55:10.632 --> 00:55:14.072
lines with varying expression levels of ENPP3,

927
00:55:14.672 --> 00:55:17.992
as well as an ENPP3 knockout or a negative cell line.

928
00:55:18.632 --> 00:55:21.312
And we see that JNJ-2175

929
00:55:21.792 --> 00:55:25.532
demonstrates a potent dose-dependent cytotoxicity

930
00:55:26.152 --> 00:55:27.892
on all of the positive cell lines,

931
00:55:28.772 --> 00:55:31.171
when compared to the isotype control ADC.

932
00:55:31.632 --> 00:55:35.472
However, no cytotoxicity was seen in the

933
00:55:35.492 --> 00:55:37.052
ENPP3 negative cell line.

934
00:55:38.372 --> 00:55:42.312
In addition to the direct killing that we're seeing here, we also looked

935
00:55:42.412 --> 00:55:46.352
at bystander activity, which as I previously described, is one of

936
00:55:46.412 --> 00:55:48.442
the key components with this platform.

937
00:55:49.212 --> 00:55:52.662
So to do this, we actually mixed or co-cultured

938
00:55:53.092 --> 00:55:56.612
an ENPP3 positive cell line, shown here in red

939
00:55:56.672 --> 00:56:00.632
fluorescence at the bottom, with an ENPP3 negative cell

940
00:56:00.672 --> 00:56:03.432
line that is shown in green fluorescence.

941
00:56:04.132 --> 00:56:07.152
And what we saw here is we did see,

942
00:56:08.252 --> 00:56:12.012
over time, a time course which is shown at the top, a

943
00:56:12.232 --> 00:56:15.932
potent killing of the ENPP3 negative cell line in the

944
00:56:15.952 --> 00:56:19.772
presence of JNJ-2175, only when they are

945
00:56:19.792 --> 00:56:22.552
co-cultured with the ENPP3 positive cell line.

946
00:56:23.392 --> 00:56:27.192
And as a control in this assay, we also ran our

947
00:56:27.232 --> 00:56:31.212
ENPP3 antibody that was conjugated with MMAF, which

948
00:56:31.392 --> 00:56:33.672
as we all know, does not have any bystander effect.

949
00:56:34.292 --> 00:56:37.852
And as you can see on the graph on the top, we didn't see any

950
00:56:37.912 --> 00:56:41.552
killing of the ENPP3 negative cell line.

951
00:56:41.952 --> 00:56:45.542
So this confirms that we both have potent direct killing, but

952
00:56:45.632 --> 00:56:48.552
also bystander activity with our molecule.

953
00:56:49.732 --> 00:56:53.192
And finally, we looked at the in vivo efficacy of our

954
00:56:53.212 --> 00:56:56.812
molecule on a panel of both cell line-derived and

955
00:56:56.972 --> 00:56:58.572
patient-derived xenograft models.

956
00:56:59.192 --> 00:57:03.112
And here I'm showing three different PDX models

957
00:57:03.192 --> 00:57:06.452
from both non-small cell lung cancer as well as RCC,

958
00:57:07.112 --> 00:57:11.012
with a range of ENPP3 expression. And as you can

959
00:57:11.112 --> 00:57:14.752
see across all three models, we see a dose-dependent

960
00:57:14.812 --> 00:57:18.382
anti-tumor efficacy with JNJ-2175,

961
00:57:18.872 --> 00:57:22.252
with complete regressions observed in all three models.

962
00:57:22.982 --> 00:57:26.212
So this kind of confirms the activity of our molecule

963
00:57:27.712 --> 00:57:29.552
pre-clinically in vivo as well.

964
00:57:30.992 --> 00:57:34.092
So with that, in summary, I showed you how

965
00:57:34.212 --> 00:57:37.632
ENPP3 is a novel target with broad

966
00:57:37.712 --> 00:57:41.572
expression in several solid tumors, and also having epically

967
00:57:41.652 --> 00:57:44.232
restricted expression in normal tissues.

968
00:57:45.012 --> 00:57:48.462
In terms of the actual molecule, our lead molecule,

969
00:57:48.552 --> 00:57:52.472
JNJ-2175, has a high-affinity ENPP3

970
00:57:52.612 --> 00:57:56.332
specific bivalent antibody that is site-specifically

971
00:57:56.392 --> 00:58:00.232
conjugated to a novel MTI-based payload, which

972
00:58:00.272 --> 00:58:02.592
shows controlled by standard activity.

973
00:58:03.492 --> 00:58:06.602
And in terms of the key pre-clinical characterization,

974
00:58:07.412 --> 00:58:10.882
we observed favorable biophysics and developability profile,

975
00:58:11.532 --> 00:58:15.012
and I showed you data that shows we have potent in vitro

976
00:58:15.152 --> 00:58:18.192
ENPP3 specific binding, rapid

977
00:58:18.372 --> 00:58:22.352
internalization, cytotoxic activity in vitro along

978
00:58:22.372 --> 00:58:26.312
with bystander activity, as well as a robust anti-tumor efficacy

979
00:58:26.492 --> 00:58:26.992
in vivo.

980
00:58:27.812 --> 00:58:31.532
Finally, we've also completed our IND-enabling non-human

981
00:58:31.632 --> 00:58:35.412
primate studies, and we see that the molecule is tolerated

982
00:58:35.652 --> 00:58:39.232
in non-human primate studies, as well as demonstrated a

983
00:58:39.272 --> 00:58:41.972
favorable pharmacokinetic profile.

984
00:58:42.032 --> 00:58:45.932
So currently, our molecule is in Phase 1 dose-escalation

985
00:58:46.012 --> 00:58:46.352
study.

986
00:58:48.192 --> 00:58:52.152
So with that, I'd like to thank everyone who's been part

987
00:58:52.212 --> 00:58:56.192
of this great team, and also thanks to our collaborators

988
00:58:56.272 --> 00:59:00.252
at Mirsana or Day One. And finally, a special thanks to all the

989
00:59:00.292 --> 00:59:03.292
patients and families who are part of the clinical trial.

990
00:59:03.392 --> 00:59:07.072
And of course, thanks everyone for your attention. Be happy to take any questions.

991
00:59:18.732 --> 00:59:20.592
Looks like we have one question here in the center.

992
00:59:21.312 --> 00:59:21.532
Sorry.

993
00:59:22.692 --> 00:59:24.252
Thank you for this excellent talk.

994
00:59:24.372 --> 00:59:27.658
Really interesting.Empp3 has been

995
00:59:27.728 --> 00:59:31.668
pursued a few times, and one of the

